The wildest aspect of the wildest deal of 2024 has to be the
handshake agreement between Shari Redstone, the owner of Paramount Global, =
and David Ellison, the Oracle heir who searched his father=E2=80=99s couch =
cushions for most of the $8 billion he spent to buy it from her. Ellison, a=
s I reported more than a year ago now, promised from the onset of talks tha=
t he wouldn=E2=80=99t turn around and flip the storied film and television =
company to another bidder. Yes, he will likely cleave off some lesser asset=
s=E2=80=94a dying cable network here, a
streaming joint venture there, $2 billion in cost cuts planned overall=E2=
=80=94but that=E2=80=99s just triage.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In the great race to consolidate Hollywood for the digital age=E2=80=94a mo=
vement that, in 2024, led far too many industry moguls to embarrass themsel=
ves by publicly cheerleading for M&A activity that would wipe out entire st=
udios and decimate the creative output they claim to care about=E2=80=94Red=
stone liked
Ellison=E2=80=99s pitch because it was the opposite. He and his father woul=
d buy her studio and leverage the family=E2=80=99s wealth to, ultimately, t=
ry to save it.

=C2=A0

That informal covenant=E2=80=94one of many, many odd aspects of the Paramou=
nt/Skydance transaction that unfolded through most of a tumultuous 2024=E2=
=80=94was more appealing to Redstone than might be expected. If she had sim=
ply chosen to auction off her family=E2=80=99s
media assets one by one, few would have blamed her. As the controlling shar=
eholder of National Amusements Inc.=E2=80=94which in turn owns Paramount, w=
hich itself comprises everything from CBS to BET to Paramount+ to the studi=
o lot and the flowers on Michael Bay Avenue=E2=80=94that was her right, and=
 probably would have netted her more.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But she didn=E2=80=99t.

